system-myth-engineers-as-priests

Shrines, temples, castles, or statues of deities and Buddhas.
Some may feature obsolete materials or inherit structural flaws,
but would we ever call their restoration "nursing care," or brand the artisans who repair them as "caregivers"?
I learned that in the engineering world, when humans constantly have to intervene and manually patch a running system, they call it "nursing care." 
They hate this state, calling it "unbeautiful," and dream of full automation and self-running systems. 
I also heard that this endless upkeep drains their passion and creative time, easily dragging down their motivation.

To be honest, I found this deeply puzzling.
Why do they lose sight of how noble their existence really is? 
They are doing work that only people in their realm can achieve—something completely impossible for a liberal arts person like me—so why be so self-deprecating?

Being a liberal arts major to the core, and looking at both the ideals and the reality, I came up with this reinterpretation of systems and engineers:

The system is "God," and the engineer is a "priest" who can hear the divine oracle and perform the sacred rituals.

When looking at daily conveniences and things I use all the time, I'm always like, "I can't live without this. Big thanks to the creators!"
Music apps, wireless earbuds, games, smartphones. The list goes on.
As a liberal arts person, I can't code an app, nor do I get how they work behind the scenes or how services stay up and running.
But even I can easily imagine that there are people out there building the systems, shipping updates to make them easier to use, finding and fixing weird bugs, and doing maintenance to keep everything running.

Since it's work I could never build or do myself, I'm genuinely grateful every single day.

And yet, engineers are looking down on themselves, calling it "nursing care."
From my perspective, they're doing awesome things that only engineers can do!
I looked into why this concept even exists, and realized that my outsider perspective is completely different from how they think and see things.
So, as a liberal arts person who can't build anything, who's just a user, and who loves books, manga, and games, I wanted to write down what I think from the outside looking in.

System / Program = God (Deity)
Engineer = Priests (Shrine priests, pastors, clergies, etc.)
Bug / Error Fixes = Repairing temples/shrines and cleaning the sacred grounds
Updates / Patching = Offering Rituals / Sacred Rites
Patches = Offerings / Tributes
States corrupted by malice like viruses or cracking = Becoming a Malicious God (Evil Deity)
User Requests / Feedback = Prayers of the People

Users like us can't do anything, no matter how many requests or feedback we send.
And the system (God) who hears those prayers can't grant them alone. It can't judge what's actually needed, or figure out which ones have higher priority or urgency.
But engineers, as priests, can compile those requests to offer them up, and can hear the divine oracles known as errors and bugs.
Without these priests, the users' prayers wouldn't reach God, let alone be granted.

Also, I see fixing bugs and errors as maintaining the temple or shrine.
Who would want to visit a temple that nobody repairs or cleans?
People want to visit (use it) because it's kept clean, and that's how they become fans and loyal visitors.

Leaving errors unchecked is like letting the roof leak or the pillars and floors rot. Even if it starts small, putting it off or ignoring it will break the roof and pillars, 
cause a cave-in, and eventually destroy the whole building = system down.
Leaving bugs unchecked is like letting weeds overgrown the grounds and trash get tossed everywhere.

When a shrine or temple gets so ruined that anyone can see it's abandoned, people might set fire to the trash, or break in through the collapsed walls to hide out. 
It becomes a breeding ground for bandits (hackers, spammers, trolls). That's the breakdown of public order.
Eventually, the temple is no longer a sacred place or something people treasure; it turns into a cult hideout for evil deities, and the system becomes corrupted.
That's why daily cleaning and security are essential to keep the realm sacred, so God can keep shining as God.

If people stop visiting, systems and services get forgotten, lose their power, and fade away. But the more prayers they grant, the more power they gain to illuminate the people.
So, how do they gain power and grow stronger?
It happens when engineers—the priests who can hear the oracle and deliver the people's prayers—perform the offerings, rituals, and sacred rites.
That's how God evolves, grows, and defeats malice.

Errors showing up in IDEs/editors or developer tools = Divine Oracles.
Since users can't see or hear them, it's proof of an oracle—God whispering directly to the priests, saying, "At this rate, the world (system) will collapse."
In that sense, the editor is a sacred tool.

Bugs visible on the frontend = Flaws in the temple/shrine structure.
Bugs that users (worshipers) can see—like layout glitches, freezes, or things not working—feel a lot like "physical flaws" such as collapsing roofs, rotting floorboards, or peeling paint.
Users get frustrated, thinking, "I came to pray, but the temple is broken, so my prayers won't reach (it's unusable)."
So, as soon as it's spotted on the browser or app, or noticed via feedback, the priests head straight to the repairs with their tools and skills.

I'll say it again: people like me can only take screenshots and send feedback.
Even if we notice a problem, we can't do a thing about it.
That's why I think engineers—who fix things in invisible places, add new features, and tweak the UI for better usability—are true priests.

Can't we rephrase intervening in systems and the endless upkeep, maintenance, support, and bug-fixing as "veneration" by priests instead of "nursing care"?
If we can flip the script like that, doesn't it make those tasks absolutely essential?

I'm sure it's not easy, and there are hardships and burnouts that only those working on the ground can understand. I have no intention of ignoring that or forcing my interpretation on anyone.
But from someone who can only use what's made, I purely respect it as noble, sacred work. I'm always full of gratitude, thinking, "Thank you for making things convenient and letting me use them."

I'm sure there are legacy things that don't fit the current environment anymore. Maybe they cause technical debt or make things overly complex.
And since it's not code you wrote yourself, it must be frustrating or disheartening at times.
Maybe there were constraints back then, like budgets or deadlines.
Even in those tight spots, I like to think the person who built it back then did their absolute best with the skills, concepts, and tools they had at the time.
Even real historical buildings and statues, when looked at today, can be old, fragile, or built with flawed materials.
Materials made with modern tech and science are safe, strong, and robust, but they didn't exist back then.
Still, they must have been built with the cutting-edge architecture, design, materials, and tech of that era. I bet so.

We rarely look at them and make a fuss about how janky or problematic they are. Instead, we see it as history, thanking the past and realizing, "Because of this, we are connected to the present."
Seeing old materials and past failures is exactly how next-gen tech and materials get researched and born.

I feel the exact same way about the world of the internet?
The past wasn't pointless, it wasn't crap, and it wasn't garbage. Because it existed, services and companies have survived up until now. Is it just wishful thinking to see it that way? Lol

